<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 94 / Linking of tax and benefits 'flawed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Proposals to integrate the tax and welfare benefit systems are flawed, says
a survey prepared for the Commission on Social Justice, the think-tank set
up by Mr John Smith, Labour leader, at the end of 1992.
The report by Andersen Consulting says most plans for integration are based
around two proposals - a negative income tax and a citizen's income.
A negative income tax would assess everyone using a single administrative
structure, with the government paying credits or collecting taxes according
to income. The report argues that an integrated scheme would still be likely
to need different assessment periods, with taxpayers being assessed annually
and benefit receivers weekly or monthly.
Furthermore, benefits are at present assessed on the basis of a household
unit. If this element of the system were maintained, women would lose the
right to independent taxation; but if assessment were done individually,
credits would be paid to the non-working wives of high-earning men.
The authors also argue that, because there is little overlap between
taxpayers and benefit recipients, any integrated system would probably still
retain two divisions to deal with the different groups.
A citizen's income would pay a basic income to everyone, clawing back the
cost in the form of higher taxes. The report argues that the tax increase
involved would be enormous and that incentives to work would be reduced.
The authors believe, however, that integration of tax and benefits might be
useful for specific groups such as pensioners, whose circumstances change
infrequently. For the rest of the population, 'strategic integration -
ensuring that the tax and benefits systems work together instead of creating
poverty and unemployment traps - may be more important than structural
integration'.
Integrating Tax and Benefits. The Institute for Public Policy Research,
30-32 Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA. Pounds 2.95.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
