<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 94 / Severn Trent to make pollution payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Financial Times Reporter
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Severn Trent, the privatised water utility, will make ex gratia payments
totalling Pounds 600,000 to households in the Worcester area affected by a
pollution alert, Mr Brian Duckworth, director of customer services, said
yesterday.
Meanwhile, the National Rivers Authority said it had traced the probable
cause of the contamination, which resulted in about 100,000 people being
advised not to drink tap water. The authority said it would consider this
week whether to take legal action against the polluter. 'We usually
prosecute when there has been pollution, except in very exceptional
circumstances,' it said.
Mr Duckworth said the Guaranteed Standards Scheme agreed between the
industry and Ofwat, its regulator, included payments of Pounds 10 a day
compensation when households had their water supply disconnected without
proper notice. Although supplies had not been cut in Worcester, Severn Trent
would make payments 'in the spirit of the scheme'. He added: 'We know, for
example, that people bought bottled water.'
He said about 30,000 households were affected by the scare which started on
Friday when some people complained that their tap water smelled and tasted
of paraffin.
All signs of contamination would be gone early this week, Mr Duckworth
promised. It was too early to estimate the full cost to Severn Trent - the
main consideration so far had been to restore water supplies to normal - but
it would not not be substantial. The company would cover all costs from
revenue.
Severn Trent reported pre-tax profits up 4.3 per cent to Pounds 140.8m on a
turnover of Pounds 489.8m for the half-year to September 30.
Health officials said there was no serious risk from the organic industrial
solvent that contaminated the water. The NRA said there was little damage to
the river Severn and river Roden and no sign of fish being killed. This made
tracing the source of the pollution much more difficult - it was eventually
traced to the Wem industrial estate in Shropshire.
The NRA refused to name the suspected polluter. 'There are a huge number of
discharges from this industrial estate and we will be looking at licenses
this coming week to establish what is and what is not permitted.'
</TEXT>
