<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 94 / Customs staff given performance pay targets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thousands of civil servants in Customs &amp; Excise will receive no pay rise
this year unless they reach basic performance targets.
The deal is the first of what could be a succession of innovative pay
agreements in the civil service agencies that have taken direct control over
pay negotiations for the first time.
About 65 per cent of all 540,000 civil servants will have their pay set by
their agency this year, rising to 90 per cent next year. A few
organisations, such as the Inland Revenue, have already devolved bargaining.
The Customs &amp; Excise deal, which the unions hope might set a trend, will
increase the pay bill by about 2.6 per cent. However the unions claim that
it will increase the pay of some clerical workers by more than 5 per cent.
There will be no pay rise at all for senior or junior staff who do not reach
basic performance targets, but the unions say this is unlikely to affect
more than a few dozen people.
For higher executive officers and grades below them, pay will rise in steps
 -related to performance - from 4.5 per cent to 6.5 per cent. As the pay
deal covers a 14-month period the rise will be slightly lower in annual
terms.
The Customs &amp; Excise agreement involves a complete overhaul of the previous
complex pay grading structure and provides both more flexibility and a
higher performance-pay element.
Mr Mike King, who negotiated the deal for the NUCPS civil service union,
said that in spite of the unhappy experience with some performance pay
systems the union was confident that the system would work well. He added:
'The important thing is that we have shown that delegated bargaining can
produce the goods.'
Other big agencies such as the Benefits Agency and the Employment Service
are similarly overhauling their pay systems, but have not yet reached
agreement on this year's pay rise.
Some agencies, such as the Driving Standards Agency, are likely to 'shadow'
the outcome of the central bargaining undertaken by the Treasury. This still
affects about one third of all civil servants.
Those core negotiations are expected to produce a rise of around 2.5 per
cent, although they are at present stalled. Union officials say that the
Treasury is keen for several agencies to conclude their pay negotiations
before the core agreement is concluded so that the temptation to shadow it
will be avoided.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
