<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 94 / Golden Virginia is chilled by realities: Mrs Bottomley is
quietly agitating for a move to a safer department as the troubled NHS is
returned to the political front-burner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Suddenly it seems to be going wrong. The National Health Service, no longer
immune from the grim realities of the government's finances, has returned to
the front-burner of politics.
For nearly two years the NHS has been kept off newspaper front pages. The
Labour charge in the 1992 general election that the government would
privatise the most cherished pillar of the welfare state has been put to
rest.
The new internal market in state health care has been entrenched. The
essential characteristic of the market - a split between the purchasers and
providers of health care - looks irreversible.
The new trust hospitals and general practitioner fundholders have boasted
with some justification that they are providing better care and shorter
waiting lists. Not so long ago Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary,
was tipped by her more excitable admirers as a future contender for the Tory
leadership.
Mrs Bottomley must have known it could not last. Faced with a Pounds 50bn
borrowing requirement the Treasury called a halt last autumn to the rapid
growth in NHS spending. The health secretary began quietly agitating for a
move to a less dangerous department in this summer's cabinet reshuffle.
But the speed and intensity of health's return to the front pages has
dismayed Tory MPs. What one minister calls the 'smile-and-it-will-go-away
approach', which has seen Mrs Bottomley get through previous scrapes, no
longer seems to be working. Unsympathetic colleagues are suggesting that,
now the going is getting rough, Mr Major must keep her on at health.
Headlines highlighting the fat salaries and expensive perks paid to the new
breed of NHS administrators have been accompanied by a spate of damaging
incidents at trust hospitals.
Reports of elderly patients being denied treatment because they are not
covered by the contracts signed by trusts and local health authorities make
for very bad politics. So does evidence that the new GP fundholding system
is allowing some patients to jump hospital queues.
There are other problems. Mrs Bottomley's rationalisation of health care in
London has provoked a damaging political backlash ahead of next month's
critical local elections.
Her assumption that everyone would agree that London consumed a
disproportionate share of NHS resources failed to take account of the
powerful public support for the capital's teaching hospitals.
In particular she misjudged the strength of opposition against the plan to
allow the renowned specialist departments at Guy's hospital to be threatened
by merger with neighbouring St Thomas's.
The campaign to save Guy's, led by Mr Simon Hughes, the Liberal Democrat MP,
has the tacit support of prominent Conservatives. Many of the wealthy
benefactors who have poured millions of pounds in charitable donations to
develop Guy's have traditionally helped to fill Conservative party coffers.
Ministers have been told those funds could well dry up if the merger goes
ahead. What would in effect be the closure of Guy's is regarded as a bad
mistake by Tory as well as opposition MPs.
The health secretary has also come under fire in Whitehall for failing to
get to grips with the burgeoning administrative staff in the NHS. The public
criticism of NHS bureaucracy in Wales voiced by Mr John Redwood, the Welsh
secretary, has seriously undermined Mrs Bottomley's efforts to defuse the
issue in England. It does not help when health authority auditors uncover
payments of more than Pounds 200,000 to cover the relocation expenses of a
senior trust executive.
But the government's problems with the NHS run much deeper than the
coincidence of a few bad headlines. The real causes are rooted in money.
For all the opposition's complaints about 'underfunding' the government has
poured money into the NHS over the past few years to lubricate the changes
to a market-based system.
The creation of an internal market was always bound to expose the rationing
of provision which has been a feature of the NHS since its inception. There
is nothing new about patients being turned away from hospitals and
intolerable waits in accident and emergency units.
But real annual increases in resources of 4 per cent and above since the
late 1980s have clouded the transparency promised by the internal market.
They have obscured also the fact that the new system gives much more power
to health producers than to consumers. Instead of money following patients
the sick have found themselves chasing the money.
The financial cushion is now disappearing. Last year's public spending
settlement provided for growth in the NHS's Pounds 30bn budget of less than
1 per cent annually for the three financial years 1994-95 to 1996-97.
District health authorities and hospital trusts are now adjusting to the
harsher financial climate.
There are other resources available - through productivity and efficiency
gains - but no one in Whitehall doubts that in the run-up to the next
general election available resources will fall significantly short of
demands on the service.
Longer waiting lists and well-paid bureaucrats are an explosive political
mix. Opposition parties will exploit every story of managerial extravagance,
and there will be many more, to attack the health service reforms. Mrs
Bottomley is discovering that for Conservative governments there is only one
route to peace in the NHS - money.
</TEXT>
<XX>
