<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 94 / DTI starts talks about Post Office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry has begun consultations to help the
government decide whether to include a bill to change the Post Office's
status in next year's parliamentary timetable.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, is one of a number of
ministers involved in meetings aimed at determining how to proceed.
One individual familiar with the position said: 'The department is keen to
come to some conclusions.' Ministers were 'coming to a period' where the
question of whether to legislate in the autumn parliamentary session 'has
got to be decided upon'.
Pressure on the government to determine a course of action is mounting both
because ministers are already in the preliminary stages of drawing up a list
of bills for the next session and because of the comments of the Post
Office's senior management.
Mr Bill Cockburn, the organisation's chief executive, last week fired the
latest shot in a long-running campaign for privatisation by claiming that a
quarter of the UK's 20,000 post offices could close unless the corporation
was given commercial freedom.
The government - which has been reviewing the Post Office's future for 21
months - will have to decide between about five options, ranging from the
status quo to full privatisation.
Mr Heseltine has made clear that he favours privatisation but many Tory MPs
for rural areas believe the Post Office would close uneconomic sub-post
offices after privatisation.
</TEXT>
