<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 94 / Growth in retail sales slows down ahead of tax rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK retail sales grew only slowly in March, according to the latest
distributive trades survey from the Confederation of British Industry. The
survey will be seen as further evidence that consumers have become cautious
ahead of this month's tax increases.
Official retail sales figures will be published by the Central Statistical
Office on Thursday. The consensus forecast among analysts is for a 0.3 per
cent volume increase between February and March, giving an annual growth
rate of 2.7 per cent.
If the retail sales figures announced on Thursday are weak, hopes of an
early interest rate cut will increase. The recently published minutes of
meetings between Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor of the exchequer, and Mr
Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, showed that the chancellor
was worried about the potential impact of this month's tax increases on the
recovery.
Mr Clarke and Mr George agreed at their meeting on March 2 that signs of
weakening in the recovery, provided they were accompanied by news that
inflation was under control, might herald a cut.
Friday's statistics on retail prices, which showed a fall in underlying
inflation to an annual rate of 2.4 per cent in March, met one of the
necessary conditions.
The CBI survey shows that the balance of retailers reporting an increase in
sales in March, compared with a year ago, was 12 percentage points.
The balances in early 1994 have been much lower than the levels of 20-30
points recorded in the second half of 1993. Figures are calculated by
deducting the proportion of those experiencing a decrease in sales from
those reporting an increase.
Mr Nigel Whittaker, chairman of the CBI's distributive trades survey panel,
said 'the modest growth in retail sales in March is perhaps a further
indicator of the uncertainty facing consumers'.
Small shops lead slide in optimism, Page 6
</TEXT>
