<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 94 / Food &amp; Drink: Afrikaner food: will it get your vote? - A
look at how Boers and Malay slaves contributed to the specific character of
South African food
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HEATHER PARKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the good old bad old days, when the right-wing, extra-right wing and
far-right wing had it all their own way in South Africa, election days were
feast days. On school playing fields and in scout halls across the land,
spick-and-span candidates proffered honesty and koeksisters (a kind of
crisp, plaited doughnut steeped in spiced syrup).
Party-faithful mums beamed family values as they flipped thick, frangrant
pannekoeke (pancakes) over portable burners.
In the run-up to this country's first democratic election on April 27, the
National Party has expanded on the old successful formula. Come hear us
speak, they said to the poverty-stricken newly-enfranchised masses, and
there will be food there.
So the masses came, and indeed there was food. Great pots of steaming putu
(an African staple, stiff maize porridge), vats of sweet tomato-and-onion
sous (relish), thick curls of boerewors (traditional spiced sausage) sending
fragrant smoke abroad as they sizzled over barbecues.
'We say: go to their meetings, eat their food . . . and then vote for us,'
was Nelson Mandela's rejoinder to that particular election ploy.
But perhaps the ANC, and the rest, should not underestimate the seductive
power of Afrikaner food. At its best it can steal your heart: whether it can
also steal your vote remains to be seen.
Like the language itself, traditional Afrikaner food is a composite of many
influences. It owes much to its Dutch ancestry, something to the English
fellow-colonialists, and much to the 1820 French Huguenot settlers.
But South African cuisine gets its specific character from two things: the
hot Great Trek across the vast interior, when the Boers moved inland to get
away from English rule in the Cape, and to the Malay slaves who were brought
to Cape colony 300 years ago.
Dried food - most famously biltong - is one of the successes of the Trek.
Spicier than jerky, biltong is beef or game which has been marinated in
spiced vinegar then studded with roasted coriander seeds and air-dried. It
lasted for months as the ox wagons jolted across the arid plains in search
of the promised land.
Lack of refrigeration was just one problem facing ox-wagon cooks. Lack of
cookers was another. Fresh food had to be cooked in a pot or over coals. The
barbecue - braaivleis in Afrikaans - is probably South Africa's trademark
cuisine.
Sunday afternoons in the suburbs are characterised by gourmands in witty
plastic aprons waving tongs like wands over fires. Purists get pedantic
about the perfect boerewors, or the kind of wood necessary to produce the
perfect coals. No conclusion has been reached on either front.
The other legacy of the great trek - and the fact that 60 per cent of South
African households are still not electrified - is potjiekos literally, pot
food. The settlers were hauled up Africa by oxen, which did double duty by
filling the bellies of those they transported. Veteran trek-oxen are tough
in the extreme: long, slow cooking was the only way to tenderise the meat,
and bredie, or stew, is the result.
Before leaving the Cape, the trekkers had picked up some useful ways with
spices from the Malays, which no doubt helped. The pot in question was then
 -and still is - iron-black, three-legged and round-bellied.
You fill it with whatever you fancy, and when the fire burns low, you heave
it onto the coals and sit back with beer and biltong. Some hours later, all
will be ready. More mythology attaches to potjiekos than almost any other
South African food. There are potjiekos festivals across the land, and
recipes are guarded fanatically.
A bredie does not have to be made in a potjie. Perfectly delicious ones are
dished up in restaurants which have never seen an open fire. The many forms
of bredie are well worth exploring - most piquant is tamatie (tomato)
bredie, most poetic is waterblummetjiebredie, variously translated as
pondweed stew and water lily stew.
Springtime in the Cape is marked by the appearance of sweet-scented white
water lilies. (Aponogeton distachyos). The flowers are picked in the bud
stage and impart a lovely green freshness to the mutton with which the dish
is made. Very little else is added - a handful of sorrel plucked from where
it grows alongside the lilies (OK, a squeeze of lemon will do), some
seasoning, a grate of nutmeg.
More profound than the Great Trek is the Malay influence on Cape cooking.
The Cape Malays as an ethnic group are somewhat misnamed: the slaves spoke
Malay, but came from Java. Cape Malay cuisine is thus predominantly
Indonesian in origin, although heavily influenced by Indian cooking. Since
Malay cooks were much sought after in the kitchens of the Dutch settlers,
traditional Dutch dishes soon acquired a sprinkling of nutmeg here, a puff
of cinnamon there. The harvest of the seas was scented with golden turmeric,
cumin and jeera made their way into meat marinades.
The lack of wine and brandy - both of which South Africa has produced in
quantity since the early days - can probably be attributed to the Moslem
Malay influence. But South Africa was not built on meat alone. Indigenous
vegetables include sweet potatoes, butternut, gem squash and the like.
Butternut is held to be as close to heaven as a gourd can be. Simply roasted
whole, its dense orange, sweet, smooth flesh is the perfect accompaniment to
just about anything. It is combined with carrots or apricots to make
delcious soups; steamed or boiled with cinnamon and mashed, it can melt the
most recalcitrant meat-eater.
With some exceptions, like the ubiquitous melktert - a kind of custard pie
dusted with cinnamon - and koeksisters, traditional deserts rely on the
abundance of local fruits.
Extremely popular is a date tart rather like pecan nut pie in appearance,
over which ladles of brandy syrup are poured while the tart is hot, and
which is served with thick cream.
Fruit fritters and salads are common, and stewed guavas served with custard
are what roly-poly is to boarding-school dinners in England.
The bad news for visitors to South Africa is that restaurants specialising
in local cuisine are much less in evidence than Italian or American-style
restaurants. The country's top restaurants all specialise in French fare. So
getting a South African meal in South Africa is rather like . . . well,
finding traditional British cooking in Britain.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ZAZ  South Africa, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P5812 Eating Places.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT942-15096</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EDQALAEOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940416
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 94 / Food &amp; Drink: Sweet steak draw - As South Africa struggles
in the world spotlight, Weekend FT looks at how food and drink has played a
part in the country's culture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILES MACDONOGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It augured well. Opposite me on the London Underground were three young
South Africans. The men were speaking Afrikaans, but clearly the woman was
less happy in this language: 'Where do we get off?' she asked in English.
'Shepherd's Bush', said one of the men. Perhaps they too were dining at The
Rotisserie, London's South African restaurant. Like the duc des Esseintes in
Joris Karl Huysman's A Rebours (Against Nature), who learned all he wanted
to know about Britain from visiting an English tavern in Paris, I aimed to
glean the maximum amount about South African food from a restaurant in
London.
The Rotisserie did not give an overwhelmingly South African impression. I
asked the patient and good-natured manager what I should eat.
'Have the tiger prawns and the peri-peri (chilli sauce)'. He said. 'Do I get
Mrs Ball's chutney with that?' 'No, you eat that with your steak'. Steak, he
said, was a typical South African dish, which did not make South Africa
sound very different to the US, Australia or Ireland.
'You have great meat here', he said, 'but you don't know how to cook it. In
South Africa we know how to treat good meat.' The meat arrived. It had
indeed been treated; bathed in a sweet marinade which not everyone at my
table liked. Mrs Ball's chutney was also rather sweet.
The atmosphere was young and fun. There were South African wines and good,
juicy steaks; but I was going to have to look elsewhere if I was to discover
real South African food. One excellent tip I received was to call Emory St
Marcus, owner of St Marcus Fine Foods, in Putney, south London. St Marcus is
the man who supplies homesick South Africans with their needs, from biltong
to chocolate bars.
Biltong is dried meat in the manner of viande des grisons bresaola or
Bundnerfleisch. The meat is salted, marinated and dried. The word derives
from 'buttock-tongue' because it was cut from the buttock, and looked like a
tongue.
Biltong can be made from any animal. There is currently some speculation as
to whether we will see ostrich biltong in the UK once the new British
ostrich farm is up and running. Game of all sorts is used and both St
Marcus, and Susman's Best Beef Biltong in Sussex makes a venison version.
The difference between biltong and the Swiss and Italian versions seems to
lie in the marinades. Basic St Marcus biltong has a lot of coriander in the
marinade. Pre-cut, it tends to dry out. I much enjoyed the Susman 'wild
venison' - gaminess seems to add a dimension to biltong.
Also on the dry side is Droewors, which St Marcus compares to the German
Landjager.
Sosaties are South African kebabs. St Marcus makes versions from beef, lamb
and pork. The highly-spiced meat is alternated with pieces of fruit:
apricots and pineapple. More to my taste was boerewors, the finely-minced
beef sausage which comes in a coil like a Cumberland sausage. The basic
mixture of 87 per cent beef and rusk is marinated in vinegar before being
filled into runners.
Susman's supplies a good many of the top shops in London. St Marcus offers
anything from South African fruit juices and wines to some of the more
important staples of the Capetown table such as monkey gland sauce and
peri-peri.
Information: The Rotisserie, 56 Uxbridge Road, London W12. Tel:
081-743-3028. St Marcus Fine Foods, 1 Rockingham Close, off Priory Lane,
Roehampton, London SW15. Tel: 081-878-1898. Susman's Best Beef Biltong, 36
Hillcrest Road, Newhaven, Sussex. Tel: 0273-516160.
</TEXT>
<XX>
