<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 94 / Defiant Bosnian Serbs blast into Gorazde
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD MORTIMER and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bosnian Serbs, defying western air power and diplomatic pressure,
blasted their way into the town of Gorazde last night and urged its Moslem
defenders to surrender.
Senior US officials, who held an emergency meeting in Washington to discuss
the enclave's virtual collapse, said the Serbs were in control of all
strategic points.
One member of Britain's elite Special Air Services died in hospital after
being evacuated from Gorazde by helicopter with serious wounds, while
another injured British soldier remained in the town after the rescue
mission treated him.
The other United Nations personnel in the town, believed to number about 14,
were taking shelter in the besieged city centre as UN authorities considered
ways to ensure their safety.
The Bosnian Serb army said it would guarantee the safety of any of Gorazde's
65,000 residents who took refuge behind its lines. This amounted to an
ultimatum to civilians to leave the city centre.
Mr Yasushi Akashi, the UN special envoy in former Yugoslavia, told Bosnia's
Moslem leaders, who were furious over the collapse of Gorazde, that the UN
had considered ordering fresh air strikes against the Serbs but dropped the
idea after the wounded soldier was evacuated.
Mr Akashi made clear the rescue mission had been possible only because of a
short-lived ceasefire arrangement with the Serbs.
The collapse of Gorazde represents a massive blow to the prestige of the
western governments which had declared the town a safe area and pledged to
protect UN personnel.
The attackers' success in Gorazde brings them within striking distance of
their long-standing aim of linking eastern Bosnia with Serbia.
Earlier, a French jet circling Gorazde was hit in the tail by anti-aircraft
guns but managed to return safely to the aircraft carrier Clemenceau in the
Adriatic. The Bosnian Serbs denied firing on the aircraft, although they had
earlier issued threats to shoot down Nato aircraft.
The Serb stranglehold on Gorazde forced waves of local inhabitants to flee
from outlying villages into the town centre. Many of the enclave's 65,000
inhabitants are already refugees.
Mr William Perry, the US defence secretary, said he hoped the Serb action
was not a 'prelude to more vigorous military action elsewhere'.
The US said last night it was sending extra troops to the former Yugoslav
republic of Macedonia, bringing its presence there to about 500, but it has
made clear it will not send ground troops to Bosnia unless there is an
overall settlement.
Lord Owen's return, Page 9
</TEXT>
