</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 94 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Zurich up in delayed reaction
to rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Better news from the US helped bourses mount a gentle recovery, writes Our
Markets Staff.
ZURICH picked up the pace as industrials took advantage of the strength of
the dollar, and in a delayed reaction to Thursday's discount rate cut. The
SMI index rose 29.2 to 2,872.9, little changed on the week. Analysts noted,
however, that while the financial sector was firmer on the day, its
lacklustre performance in the wake of the SNB's move on rates indicated that
further market weakness could be in store next week.
Currency considerations helped Nestle SFr15 higher to SFr1,249: the group
reiterated its strategic interest in L'Oreal following the French cosmetics
group's announcement on Thursday of a restructuring of its holdings.
Ciba registered rose SFr15 to SFr945 ahead of Monday's first quarter sales
figures, and Roche certificates by SFr40 to SFr7,080 as analysts looked for
a rise of at least 20-30 per cent in 1993 earnings on Tuesday.
Strong cyclicals featured Brown Boveri, up SFr30 to SFr1,287 on London
buying. Oerlikon-Buhrle rose SFr7 to SFr168 and Alusuisse added SFr11 to
SFr656.
Against the trend, Sulzer lost SFr35 to SFr1,010 in further response to this
week's profits forecast.
FRANKFURT kicked effectively in the post-bourse for the first time in days,
the Ibis-indicated Dax climbing to 2,211.92 after a rise of just 1.71 to
2,200.42 on the official session which left it slightly down on the week.
Turnover rose from DM9.5bn to DM10.3bn. Even in the morning, Dax
constituents showed more of a pattern than in recent days, with the weakness
of banks on the Jurgen Schneider property situation more than balanced by
strength in automotive stocks.
The positive aspects of that trend were extended in the post bourse.
Daimler, just DM2 higher at DM874.50 on the session, put on another DM5.50
in the afternoon and Volkswagen moved from a DM9.50 rise to DM519.50 to one
of DM18, at DM528. VW had been strong against the market over the last
month, quarter and 12-month period, but Goldman Sachs said it had further to
go, projecting a prospective p/e of just over 7 on 1997 earnings.
PARIS closed at the day's high as the market was lifted by late futures
activity. The CAC-40 index put on 20.54 or 1 per cent to 2,159.59, for a
week's rise of 2 per cent.
Schneider was heavily sought, rising FFr23.409 or 5.4 per cent to FFr452.90,
following the release of better than expected 1993 results. The electrial
equipment group also raised the dividend, by 50 centimes to FFr7, and saw
growth continuing throughout 1994.
Saint-Louis added FFr28 to FFr1,775 on news that it was to merge its
prepared food business with BSN, up FFr8 to FFr850.
AMSTERDAM was particularly active as options expired during the afternoon,
with the AEX index reaching a session high of 428.42 before slipping back to
close up 1.43 at 425.12.
The index recorded a 2.3 per cent gain on the week.
Royal Dutch, up Fl4.30 on the day, and 3.3 per cent on the week at Fl207.50,
was the most active issue as oil prices and stocks firmed in London on
bullish expectations.
Nedlloyd, due to release figures next week, added Fl1.10 to Fl74.90. Goldman
Sachs noted yesterday that the shipping and distribution group had been one
of the market's best performing stocks recently. Most of this
outperformance, Goldman added, occured in the second half of 1993 following
better-than-expected results and forecasts of a profit in 1994, which the
investment bank estimated at Fl127m.
MILAN gave up some of an early advance in a round of brief but heavy selling
by domestic funds as the conservative alliance failed to have its nominees
elected as parliamentary presidents, and Mr Silvio Berlusconi raised the
spectre of fresh elections. The Comit index finished 13.20 or 1.7 per cent
ahead at 800.32 for a 5.9 per cent rise on the week.
Trading was again heavy as more than 180 new shares and warrants joined the
screen-based trading system, bringing an end to open outcry in Milan.
Blue chip industrial issues, which had led the market, saw their gains
restrained. Fiat rose L42 to L6,569, after a high of L6,790, and Montedison
edged L3 ahead to L1,507 after a peak of L1,558 in heavy volume of 53.9m
shares.
The telecommunications issues were a bright spot: Sip rose L48 to L4,961,
Italcable L67 to L11,539 and Cogefar L61 to L2,616. But profits were taken
in the insurers after their recent surge: Alleanza fell L296 to L18,974,
Fondiaria lost L230 to L13,935 and SAI gave up L491 to L21,693.
MADRID remained nervous about the appearance of Mr Mariano Rubio before
congress, after hours yesterday, to answer questions about his personal
financial dealings while he governed the Bank of Spain. The general index
fell another 2.78 to 318.86, 2.1 per cent lower on the week.
