<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 94 / World Stock Markets: Japan hopes to build on first quarter
rally - Emiko Terazono finds equity investors are cautious
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Japanese shares have shown surprising resilience against the recent turmoil
in global stock markets, the yen's volatility and domestic political
instability.
Share prices were supported by capital flows as overseas investors shifted
their funds from south-east Asian markets to Japan. The Nikkei index rose
9.7 per cent during the first quarter and outperformed the rest of the
Pacific Rim by 45 per cent.
The lack of downside risk compared to other Asian markets and hopes of an
economic recovery led by a rise in consumption later on in the year prompted
buying by overseas investors. During the first two months of this year,
overseas investors bought a total of Y2,250bn in Japanese stocks, countering
heavy selling by domestic corporations which were selling their holdings to
supplement slack profits.
The question is whether the strength will carry on through the second
quarter. Investors had initially hoped that domestic institutions would
start allocating cash into the stock market in the business year following
allocation meetings which started at the end of last month.
However, with bond yields still around 4 per cent, views among analysts are
currently mixed as Japanese institutions may choose to invest in the bond
market instead of stocks.
'Market conditions are likely to remain stodgy,' says Mr Peter Tasker,
strategist at Kleinwort Benson in Tokyo. Although the expected weakness is
unlikely to reward aggressive selling, he says, falling bond yields and the
weakening yen, which supported stocks at the start of the year, will have
less of an impact.
Earlier this week Japan's leading life assurers, large lot investors in
Japanese stocks, warned that they would remain cautious towards equities. Mr
Toshiomi Uragami, chairman of the Life Insurance Association of Japan, says
that life companies find stock investments difficult to justify due to the
low dividends, and that they will boost investment in the domestic bond
market.
NatWest Securities in London is more optimistic, believing that Japan is the
place to be this year because of the strong likelihood of a recovery in the
economy and corporate earnings.
Mr Jason James, strategist at James Capel in Tokyo, is 'neutral' about the
market. Although he feels that stocks are looking over-expensive compared to
bonds, the expected earnings recovery is beginning to become evident and
will support share prices.
Considering the sharp falls in corporate earnings over past few years, the
recovery is likely to be huge. According to James Capel, the machinery
sector is earning less than 1 per cent of its peak profits, the car sector
less than 3 per cent and electricals less than 18 per cent. Even if the
figures do not recover the peak levels of the 1980s, an earnings rebound
will signal a jump of four to five times over the next few years.
NatWest estimates the earnings rebound to be around 20 per cent for the year
ending next March. Although the price to earnings ratio of around 100 looks
expensive on the basis of such figures, it says, looking beyond 1995 the
figure does not seem too high.
For investors looking to place funds in the stock market, the
over-the-counter stock market with its small growth stocks may offer
favourable prospects.
The immediate economic outlook on the other hand remains mixed, although
some 'green shoots' indicate that the economy has hit the bottom of its
current cycle.
How much longer will the economy crawl along the bottom? So far the economy
has been helped by a rise in consumption, led by an active housing market as
real estate companies have started to put cheap condominiums on to the
market at a time of low housing loan interest rates. Housebuying has surged,
while sundries and durable good sales connected to the housing market have
also risen. The current deflation is also encouraging consumption, at least
by volume if not by value.
Whether such activity can be sustained as more companies are forced to cut
labour costs remains to be seen. Although companies will not move to lay off
their labour forces, a jump in consumer spending large enough to pull the
whole economy out of its doldrums is unlikely. Kleinwort Benson projects
real consumption settling down into an annual growth of around 1 per cent.
Mr Geoffrey Barker, economist at Baring Securities in Tokyo, says that the
volatility of the yen could prompt policy moves which would boost the
economy. He forecasts that currency speculators are likely to step up
activity ahead of the Group of Seven talks in Naples and next month's
corporate earnings results. 'If the yen moves below Y100 it is likely to
prompt a policy response, including a cut in the official discount rate and
another supplementary budget,' he says.
If economic figures released over the next few months confirm that
conditions are steadily improving, Mr Barker says that the Nikkei could
break the 21,000 level.
But caution still prevails, and Mr Mikio Fujii of Nomura Securities says
that technical resistance remains heavy around the 21,000 level on the
Nikkei 225. 'We would need very large volumes to break through,' he adds.
</TEXT>
