<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 94 / Markets Report: Sterling firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The release of a better than expected March UK retail inflation figure
yesterday gave rise to renewed optimism about the prospect of lower interest
rates, writes Philip Gawith.
Few observers believe a cut is imminent, but the case for an easing of
credit policy has been bolstered by underlying retail price inflation
falling to 2.4 per cent in March - in the lower half of the government's
target range.
The improved outlook was reflected in short sterling futures, with the June
contract closing nine basis points higher at 94.73.
Sterling was fairly stable with the trade weighted index closing at 79.9
after opening at 79.8. It closed in London at DM2.5233 after finishing on
Thursday at DM2.5239.
Elsewhere, weaker than expected March industrial production and capacity
utilisation figures in the US undermined the dollar. The US currency
finished at DM1.7124 against the D-Mark from DM1.7088 on Thursday.
Ireland joined the round of European rate cuts by lowering its short-term
facility rate to 6.50 per cent from 6.75 per cent.
Mr Gerard Lyons, chief economist at DKB International, said the good RPI
number provided confirmation that the underlying UK inflation trend was
still favourable. He doubted, however, whether it had direct policy
implications.
The recently released minutes of monthly monetary policy meetings revealed
that 'good inflation is a necessary, but not a sufficient, criterion for the
Bank of England to cut again. It would need to see a slowdown in the economy
because of higher taxes' said Mr Lyons.
The Bank of England provided Pounds 170m of late assistance to the UK money
markets. Earlier it had provided Pounds 73m assistance, compared to a
forecast shortage of Pounds 350m.
Taken together, the two US data released yesterday, were slightly weaker
than the market anticipated. Industrial production rose 0.5 per cent in
March, while capacity utilisation in mines, utilities and factories rose to
83.6 per cent from 83.4 per cent.
Although slightly below expectations, the capacity figure was not far short
of 85, historically seen as the level at which inflationary pressures are
triggered. Analysts said the data was keeping the dollar well underpinned,
but not providing fresh buying support.
Placing downward pressure on the dollar is the resurgent yen. No fresh
initiative to deal with the US/Japan trade dispute emerged from the meeting
in Marrakesh between Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, and Mr
Tsutomu Hata, the Japanese foreign minister.
Increasingly the market is tending towards the view that the dollar will
weaken further, falling through Y100 to record lows.
Elsewhere in Europe the D-Mark finished stronger against most European
currencies. The Italian lira slipped further to L956 from L954.8 as a
squabble about the election of a speaker in the Senate renewed fears about
the prospects for a stable government following the recent elections.
The Spanish peseta finished at Pta81.61 from Pta81.31, weakened apparently
by rumours that the Economics minister would be resigning.
</TEXT>
