<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 94 / International Company News: CBoT votes to opt out of
revamped Globex
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The board of directors of the Chicago Board of Trade have voted not to
participate in a restructured Globex. The move effectively ends a fractious
five-year partnership between the exchange, Reuters, and the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, and creates a potential competitor for the system.
The exit by the world's largest futures exchange further clouds plans for
the ambitious Dollars 200m project, created by Reuters as a vehicle for
round-the-clock, round-the-world futures trading.
In the two years since its launch, Globex has not met its volume or
globalisation targets, and only France's Matif has made significant use of
the system.
The CBoT says it plans to pull its contracts from Globex on April 30. After
then, only Matif and CME contracts will remain on the system.
Ms Rosalyn Wilton, Reuter's managing director for transaction products,
said: 'We're obviously disappointed by the CBoT's decision. We believe the
new Globex agreement goes a long way to provide an equitable arrangement for
new exchanges to join.'
Participation by London's Liffe is thought to be critical to Globex's
future. Mr Daniel Hodson, Liffe's chief executive, said: 'I certainly think
Globex would have more credibility if it included CBOT.'
Meanwhile, the CBoT plans to list its financial futures contracts for
after-hours trade on its own local computer network, and may extend that
trading using Bloomberg Financial Services terminals, in competition with
Globex.
</TEXT>
