<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 94 / UK Company News: Wembley losses double to Pounds 66m -
Write-downs and weak balance sheet behind sharp setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wembley, the debt-burdened stadium and greyhound track operator, yesterday
blamed large property write-downs as pre-tax losses for 1993 almost doubled
from a restated Pounds 34.1m to Pounds 65.7m.
The company said it no longer had any distributable reserves and, following
its first property valuation in three years, admitted net assets were now
worth Pounds 98.3m less than the Pounds 175.1m reported last time.
Faced with borrowings of Pounds 152.1m - equivalent to almost three times
shareholders' funds - the balance sheet proved too weak to absorb the
write-downs and the company was forced to set Pounds 48.3m against operating
profits.
Together with a further Pounds 3.2m charge for refinancing banking
facilities, exceptional items totalled Pounds 51.5m.
Those charges undermined operating profits of Pounds 11.1m (Pounds 12.7m) on
continuing activities and contributed to operating losses of Pounds 39.2m,
against a Pounds 3.7m gain last time.
The company was also hit by banking covenants requiring a Pounds 40m debt
repayment by March 31 this year, which it met only by selling non-core
subsidiaries for Pounds 24.4m and, since the 1993 year-end, disposing of a
50 per cent stake in Pacer CATS, the computer ticketing concern, for Pounds
15m.
Sir Brian Wolfson, chairman, said: 'We've been to hell and back. We were
fighting uphill to make every disposal.'
He also warned that the company - which is unable to pay the dividend on
both its ordinary and convertible preference shares - could be in breach of
its borrowing powers and would be seeking shareholder approval for revised
terms.
In addition to the Pounds 40m repaid so far, the company is committed to a
further debt reduction of up to Pounds 39.5m by the end of this year and Sir
Brian said the board was considering a court application to approve a
financial reconstruction.
Any refinancing would be used not only to reduce borrowing but to provide
fresh investment for its three divisions.
Of those divisions, the Wembley complex saw operating profits decline from a
restated Pounds 7.1m to Pounds 5.1m as bookings for the arena and stadium
declined.
The greyhound business reported virtually flat profits of Pounds 5.8m
(Pounds 5.5m), and profits in leisure services - including Pacer CATS - fell
from Pounds 2.3m to Pounds 1.9m.
Group turnover declined 21 per cent to Pounds 150.5m (Pounds 191.4m)
including a contribution of Pounds 21.6m from discontinued operations.
Describing the results as a 'watershed', Sir Brian said prospects this year
were improving and it had resolved its dispute with the Football Association
over sponsorship and television revenues.
A 10-year advertising contract has been signed with Coca-Cola and the
disposal programme was said to be largely completed.
Losses per share, however, increased from a restated 15.4p to 26.6p and Sir
Brian conceded 'we've got a big challenge ahead'.
The shares closed up 1 1/2 p at 12p.
</TEXT>
<XX>
