<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 94 / Ford to take full ownership of Hertz and raise payout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ford Motor, the US vehicle manufacturer, announced yesterday that it is to
take full ownership of its subsidiary Hertz, the world's largest car rental
company, by buying out Sweden's Volvo and the company's management, which
together own 46 per cent.
Ford also confirmed it was selling its troubled California savings and
loans, First Nationwide Bank, for Dollars 1.1bn (Pounds 745m) to
Dallas-based First Madison Bank. The carmaker also announced a 12.5 per cent
increase in its quarterly dividend - the first change since it cut the
payout in April 1991.
Ford recently increased its stake in Hertz from 49 per cent to 54 per cent
through the purchase of a 5 per cent stake held by Germany's Commerzbank. It
will now pay Dollars 145m to Volvo for its 26 per cent stake, consisting of
common and preferred stock, and will buy out the management's 20 per cent
holding for an undisclosed sum.
Mr Soren Gyll, Volvo chief executive, said the deal was part of its strategy
of sharpening its business focus. It would also improve the company's net
debt figure.
Ford said it regarded rentals as a core part of its car business. The deal
ensured excellent exposure for its products. About 70 per cent of Hertz's
vehicle purchases in the US come from Ford, while the US carmaker supplies a
third of its European fleet. Last year Hertz had net income of Dollars 53m
on turnover of Dollars 2.85bn.
Ford added that First Nationwide was being sold at a small premium above
tangible book value. Ford would take a Dollars 440m charge against
first-quarter earnings, mainly to reflect non-recovery of goodwill, as well
as reserves for losses on retained assets. Ford bought First Nationwide in
1985 for around Dollars 500m and rapidly ran into property loan problems.
Ford's quarterly dividend was raised from 40 cents to 45 cents from June 1
and the company also declared a two-for-one stock split.
The three Detroit carmakers all cut their dividends in early 1991 in the
midst of recession. Chrysler was the first to announce a raise - of one
third - unveiled in December, but GM has yet to move.
</TEXT>
